# Lord of the Keys: Interactive Game Development & One-Shotting Tests
This document serves as an architectural overview and technical review of Lord of the Keys, a simple educational platformer designed to help elementary school students improve their typing.
It outlines the product thinking (questionable), structural decisions, and technical learnings derived from taking on the challenge of building a simple platformer in HTML in under 8 hours of non-focused time.

## 1. Context & Objective
Lord of the Keys was built as a friendly challenge to myself; a buddy had also been playing around with agentic AI development who is also not a developer and had one-shotted a fairly good HTML-based spelling game for a kid using Codex.
I thought that was a really fun experiment, and wanted to see if Gemini could do the same. 

The objective of the Lord of the Keys is to provide a simple but deceptively-learning-centric game which captured the magic of early platforming games in a semi-recognizable context while still teaching valuable skills. 
Inspired by the Lord of the Rings, the game consists of 8 levels based on different locations visited in the Lord of the Rings trilogy. 
Users choose their proficiency with typing (Hobbits or Rangers) and then progress through the levels by typing the letters or words that appear on screen, navigating their characters through the level, and either avoiding or defeating LOTR-inspired enemies by typing words. 
3 bosses at the end of 3 of the levels ensure difficulty progression and are fun for the users.

Market research: none. I had access to 2 very willing testers (under 5 and under 10) and they had a lot of fun watching me try and fail at some of the workflows during the game.

## 2. Architectural Underpinnings & AI Product Thinking
I wanted very much to land the plane with a one-shot prompt, and probably could have gotten away with it if I'd either
  - a) put an hour of research into the frontend before prompting, or
  - b) accepted some of the questionable design choices of the first output

 However, I was very eager to play the game (as were my testers) so I wound up doing a lot more single-threaded feature work and bug fixes than I'd expected.

